0.title: Allergy
dlg: Although colds and seasonal allergies may share some of the same symptoms, they are different things altogether. Common colds are caused by viruses, whereas seasonal allergies are immune system reaction triggered by exposure to an allergen.

Here are the rationale we used:

  • Allergy start all of a sudden because your body is reacting to something you inhaled.
  • Cold symptoms take time to develop as the cold virus is invading the nasal passages.
  • Allergy never include fever
  • Allergy never include severe body aches
  • Allergy rarely include sore throat until later when all the drainage might have irritated the throat area.

When the cold virus first enter your nose and sinuses, they respond by making a clear mucus to help wash the virus from these areas.
Your symptoms will depend on the type of cold virus that is attacking. After 2 or 3 days, the body fights back. This change the mucus color to white or yellow.

Most symptoms due to colds that is not complicated usually takes care of itself within 10 days.

Your goal would be to shorten the duration of the cold and reduce any complications.

A cold can also lead to:

  • Ear infection
  • Bronchitis
  • Pneumonia
  • Inflammation of the sinuses.

2.title: Flu
dlg:
You should go to the emergency room only if you are very sure you have the flu. Else you will go in there and leave with the flu.
This is because, other people with the flu are coming in and you could get infected.

Suspect the flu if you have:

  • Headache
  • Nausea and vomiting
  • Feeling dizzy
  • Flushed face
  • Severe body aches
  • Been around someone with the flu lately.

If not these symptoms and you mainly have runny or stuffy nose without severe body aches, headaches or chills, then we will think cold.

Think cold if the following apply to you as much as possible:

  • No fever
  • No chills
  • More of runny or stuffy nose
  • No headache
  • No severe body ache
  • No nausea or vomiting
  • No dizziness
  • Face is not flushed.

60.header:
Can you take care of this on your own?

Or do you need to see a doctor?


It is very important to rule out the risks of complications that can be dangerous.
Let's start by doing that.

61.header: Are you over the age of 65?

62.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • The risk of complication from the flu is high at this age.
  • The flu affects the lungs and you can easily develop pneumonia.

63.header: Are you more than 3 months pregnant?

64.header:
Call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • If it turns out to be flu illness, the risk of complications are high with pregnancy.
  • Your immune system is weaker when you're pregnant making you more vulnerable to flu illness.
  • Self care is not advised.
  • You have a greater chance for serious problems for the unborn baby, including premature labor and delivery.
  • You may need antiviral medications even if it is past 48 hours.

65.header: Are you diabetic?

66.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • It is going to be harder for you to fend off the flu virus leading to complications.
  • Flu illness affects the muscles. This can cause wide variations in your blood sugar.
  • Loss of appetite and thirst would make managing your diet harder.
  • The ADA recommends checking the blood sugar at least every 3 to 4 hours and reporting any significant changes to your doctor right away. You may need more insulin if your blood sugar is too high, or less if too low.
  • People with diabetes are about three times more likely to die from flu and pneumonia. Self care is not advised.

Testing diabetes related division 1 ad spot. See what we are talking about here

67.header: Do you have heart disease?

68.header:

Here is why:

  • Your body is going to be too weak to fight off the flu.
  • You are at increased risk of having a heart attack.
  • Increased risk of experiencing flu-related complications such as pneumonia.
  • You will need to start antiviral medications as soon as possible.

110.header:
A few things to know if you have flu symptoms are listed below.


Summarized from cdc.gov

lists.title: Go to emergency room if... click to expand contents
lists.content:
• You have shortness of breath and difficulty breathing

  • Feeling dizzy all of a sudden

  • Feeling confused

  • Severe or persistently vomiting

  • Pain or pressure in the chest or abdomen

  • Purple or blue discoloration of the lips.

  • Your flu improved but then return with fever and very bad cough

Go to the emergency room only if you have these emergency warning signs of flu sickness.

Do not go if you are only mildly sick or else if you don't have the flu, you may get it from people who have it at the emergency room.

lists.title: While you are sick.. click to expand contents
lists.content:
• Stay away from others as much as possible to keep from making them sick. If you must leave home, wear a face mask if you have one or cover coughs and sneezes with a tissue.
  • Wash your hands often to keep from spreading flu to others.

  • CDC recommends you stay home from work, school, travel, shopping, social events and public gatherings for at least 24 hours after you fever is gone (without the use of fever reducing medications) except to get medical care or for other things you have to do and no one else can do for you.

  • Keep surfaces like bedside tables, surfaces in the bathroom, kitchen counters and toys for children clean by wiping them down with a household disinfectant according to directions on the product label.

  • Try to stay in a separate room from others in the household if possible.

lists.title: What to do at home: click to expand contents
lists.content:
• Avoid close contact with well people in your house so you won't make them sick

  • Designate a sick room if possible and let all sick people share that room.

  • If you have more than one bathroom, have sick people use one bathroom and well people use the other one.
  • Let each sick person have their own drinking glass, washcloth and towel.

  • If visitors must enter the sick room, they should stay away at least 6 feet away from the sick person.

  • Open a window in the sick room or if possible use a fan to keep fresh air flowing.

  • Take great steps to prevent dehydration. Drink clear fluids such as water, broth or sports drinks.

  • Check your urine color: Clear or light yellow-colored urine means you are getting enough fluid. Dark yellow may signal dehydration.

lists.title: How you might get the flu click to expand contents
lists.content:
Flu viruses travel through the air in droplets when someone with the infection coughs , sneezes or even talks. It can travel up to 6 feet away.

You can inhale the droplets directly or you can pick up the germs by touching objects where the droplets have landed, such as telephone or computer keyboards, or even door handles.

lists.content:
(These widgets will take you to CDC site)

Get a flu shot!

The best time to be vaccinated is October and November. This will give your body enough time to develop antibodies to the flu virus before the peak flu season starts. This is typically between December and March.
But remember, you can always get one later. It is better than not getting at all and it may still protect you.

3.title: Headache
dlg:
It is important to recognize what could set off some types of headaches because they can be dangerous or require treatment of the underlying cause.

For instance, dental or sinus infection could set off a headache and if not treated, the headache may not go away.

Tension headaches tend to start from the back of the head and spread towards the front.
The pain is usually like a band squeezing the head and it tends to be on both sides of the head or all over.

It may be worse in the scalp, temples, or back of the neck, and even in the shoulders.

This is because they occur when neck and scalp muscles become tense, or contract in response to something like stress, dental problems, computer work, eye strain, alcohol, caffeine use, head injury, anxiety or cold and flu.

Treatment involves:

  • Treating the pain when it happens
    For aborting attacks, injectable or nasal spray medications called triptans, dihydroergotamine, or 100% O2 may be used.
  • Preventing it from happening
    For long-term prevention, verapamil, lithium, topiramate, divalproex, or a combination of these medications may be needed. Your doctor may give you a steroid like prednisone to help prevent this temporarily until medications such as verapamil can kick in.

From the medications listed above, you can see that you must see a doctor to take care of cluster headaches. Don't even try self care with it.

Pain killers and even narcotics don't usually help with this kind of headache.

There is even no need to send you to a pharmacist, because nothing over-the-counter is going to cut this. Either, go to the emergency room or the nearest urgent care clinic.
Migraines can last hours or even days. We know all you can think of right now is to find a quiet, dark and peaceful place to just lay your head.

0.header:
The most common type of headache is tension headaches.

Headaches can be a sign of something serious going on, let's rule out situations that may require urgent care or emergency room visit.

1.header:
Is this a headache that started suddenly, coming on really fast...

...or slowly gradually making you feel it?

2.header:
Headaches starting suddenly, coming on fast, may mean something serious going on.

Let's make sure you are not looking at an emergency situation like a stroke coming on.

3.header: Is this your worst headache ever?

4.header:
Yes?
Hmmm. Let's continue cautiously.

5.header: Is this headache making you feel like vomiting?

7.header: Are you having difficulty finding words or talking with this headache?

8.header:
Emergency!
Call 911.

Here is why:

  • May be looking at a stroke in progress.

Note:
We do not advice continuing for now. You should only continue if you are not experiencing the question asked.

9.header:
Any difficulty moving your arms?

Or legs?

10.header:
Emergency!
Call 911.

Here is why:

  • Probably a stroke in progress.

Note:
We do not advice continuing for now. You should only continue if you are not experiencing the question asked.

12.header:
Emergency!
Call 911.

Here is why:

  • Possible stroke in progress.

Note:
We do not advice continuing for now. You should only continue if you are not experiencing the question asked.

13.header:
Is your vision changing since the headache started suddenly?

Like getting blurred?

15.header:
Are you experiencing drooping of one side of the face?

Or eyelid?

16.header:
Emergency!
Call 911.

Here is why:

  • Possible stroke coming on.

Note:
We do not advice continuing for now. You should only continue if you are not experiencing the question asked.

17.header:
Are you experiencing sudden numbness or weakness?

Especially on one side of the body?

18.header:
Emergency!
Call 911.

Here is why:

  • Possible stroke coming on.

Note:
We do not advice continuing for now. You should only continue if you are not experiencing the question asked.

19.header: What about losing vision on the side?

20.header:
Emergency!
Call 911.

Here is why:

  • Possible stroke coming on.

Note:
We do not advice continuing for now. You should only continue if you are not experiencing the question asked.

21.header:
Ew,
We tried to rule out stroke or a blood vessel in the brain rupturing.

Call 911 or seek emergency room visit if you are experiencing most of these symptoms:

  • Worst headache ever
  • Geting confused with this headache
  • Nausea and vomiting
  • Slurring of your speech
  • Losing vision on the side
  • Drooling
  • Vision getting blurred
  • Feeling lightheaded with severe headache.

These are the main signs and symptoms of someone having a stroke. If this does not apply to you, then let's continue

30.header: Do you have fever with this headache?

31.header:
Yes?
Headache with fever is not uncommon and may not require emergency room visit.

But let's rule out something like meningitis or encephalitis.

32.header: Any nausea and/or vomiting with this fever and headache?

34.header: Are you experiencing increased sensitivity to light?

35.header:
Go to the Emergency Room.

Here is why:

  • Need to rule out meningitis which is a medical emergency.

Would you like to see the nearest hospital?

Note:
We do not advice continuing for now. You should only continue if you are not experiencing the question asked.

36.header: What about breathing rapidly with this headache and fever?

37.header:
Go to the Emergency Room.

Here is why:

  • Need to rule out meningitis or encephalitis which is a medical emergency.

Would you like to see the nearest hospital?

Note:
We do not advice continuing for now. You should only continue if you are not experiencing the question asked.

38.header: Is your neck getting stiff?

39.header:
Go to the Emergency Room.

Here is why:

  • Possible meningitis developing.

Try touching your chin to the chest.

If the neck is so stiff that the chin cannot touch the chest, call 911.

This is serious unless you are sure it is a nerve problem or something you are familiar with like a neck injury or surgery you had.

Meningitis can quickly become a life-threatening illness. Early treatment is important.

Would you like to see the nearest hospital?

Note:
We do not advice continuing for now. You should only continue if you are not experiencing the question asked.

40.header:
Those were to rule out meningitis or encephalitis.

These can be life threatening and require emergency care.

If this does not apply to you, let's continue or else seek emergency care by going to the nearest hospital.

50.header: Are your eyes getting very red with this headache?

51.header: Let's make sure you are not looking at something very serious like glaucoma.

52.header: Are you seeing halos around lights?

53.header:
You are?
This is a symptom of glaucoma.

Let's continue and see if we can rule out glaucoma. Don't panic yet.

54.header: Do you feel like throwing up with this red eyes and headache?

55.header:
You do?
Hope we are not looking at something serious like glaucoma.

Symptoms of glaucoma include:

  • Seeing halos around lights.
  • Nausea and vomiting.

56.header: Are you having blind spots in your vision?

57.header:
Okay?
This is a symptom of glaucoma.

Symptoms of glaucoma include:

  • Seeing halos around lights.
  • Nausea and vomiting.
  • Blind spots in one's vision.

58.header: Are you losing vision to the side?

59.header:
Go to the Emergency Room.

Here is why:

Symptoms of acute closed angle glaucoma include:

  • Seeing halos around lights.
  • Nausea and vomiting.
  • Blind spots in one's vision.
  • Loss of side vision

Would you like to see the nearest hospital?

Note:
We do not advice continuing for now. You should only continue if you are not experiencing the question asked.

60.header: Is your vision getting blurred with this headache?

61.header:
Go to the Emergency Room.

Here is why:

Symptoms of acute closed angle glaucoma include:

  • Seeing halos around lights.
  • Nausea and vomiting.
  • Blind spots in one's vision.
  • Loss of side vision
  • Blurred vision

Would you like to see the nearest hospital?

Note:
We do not advice continuing for now. You should only continue if you are not experiencing the question asked.

62.header:
Ew,
Tried to rule out acute angle closure glaucoma, a medical emergency.

Damage to the optic nerve may start rapidly and if not treated within 6 to 10 hours can lead to permanent loss of vision.

If you are positive that this is not the case, then let's continue.
Else, you should start heading to the emergency room now.

70.header: Is the headache as a result of a head injury?

71.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room.

Here is why:

  • Will need further evaluation.

72.header:
Are you over 50 years old and you are experiencing throbbing pain?

With vision problems and sweating?

74.header:
What about over 50 years old and you are experiencing pain when combing your hair?

Or when chewing?

75.header:
Go to the Emergency Room.

Here is why:

  • Giant cell arteritis

Would you like to see the nearest hospital?

Note:
We do not advice continuing for now. You should only continue if you are not experiencing the question asked.

76.header: Would you say this is the worst headache you have ever had in your life?

77.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room.

Here is why:

  • Need to rule out something serious going on.

78.header:
So far we tried ruling out emergency room visit.

Some headaches may be a sign of a more serious illness. It was important we eliminated those threats.

Now, let's continue and see how we can take care of your headache.

90.header: This is a common type of headache. Let's take a look.

91.header:
Would you describe the headache as all over your head?

Not just in one point or one side.

92.header:
All over?
This is one of the signs of a tension headache.

93.header: Did this headache start at the back of the head and moved forward?

94.header:
Yes?
This is a sign and symptom of a tension type headache.

Symptoms include:

  • Headache all over the head
  • Headache starting at the back of the head and moving forward

95.header: Does this headache feel dull?

96.header:
Yes?
This is a symptom of a tension headache.

Symptoms include:

  • Headache all over the head
  • Headache starting at the back of the head and moving forward
  • Feeling dull

97.header:
Would you say it is like a tight band around your head?

Pressure-like?
(not throbbing)

98.header:
Yes?
Very likely looking at a tension headache.

Symptoms include:

  • Headache all over the head
  • Headache starting at the back of the head and moving forward
  • Feeling dull
  • Pressure-like (not throbbing)
  • Like a tight band around the head

99.header: Does this headache get worse at the end of the day?

100.header:
More than likely looking at tension headache.

Symptoms include:

  • Headache all over the head
  • Headache starting at the back of the head and moving forward
  • Feeling dull
  • Pressure-like (not throbbing)
  • Like a tight band around the head
  • Headache that gets worse at the end of the day.

101.header: Your shoulders and neck, do they somehow feel sore?

103.header:
Ew,
Those were symptoms of a tension headache.

If you think you are looking at tension headaches, let's continue and see how you can take of this with over-the-counter medications or measures.

111.header:
Have no idea?
Oh well, let's continue and see what is available over the counter for tension headache.

112.header:
High blood pressure?
Hope you are taking medication for this.

113.header:
Alright.
Continue and see what a pharmacist would recommend over the counter.

120.header: Do you get headaches often?

121.header:
Yes?
We are pretty sure you know what the triggers are, what to avoid and so on.

Stick to what usually worked for you in the past. If they don't work for you anymore, then let's continue.

122.header: Are you a male or a female?

124.header:
Female?
Is this headache related to your menstrual period?
